    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
               <p>Not included into <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/></bibl>. 
                   <bibl><ptr target="#antolini2021"/>, pp. <citedRange>46-49</citedRange> and fig. 3-4</bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name>Πρῶρος</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Θεύχρηστος" type="patronymic">Θευχρήστω</name></persName></persName>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Prôros fils de Theukhrestos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Proros son of Theuchrestos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Proros figlio di Theuchrestos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p/>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>Both names are well attested in Cyrenaica, no instance being known of them in a parental relation. The son's name is typically Cyrenaean. The father's name is less typical, but more 
             frequent. This confirms Antolini's wise conclusion that any supposed relation with contemporary persons bearing one of those names is rather hazardous.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
